"Sun W., Miura S., Sato T., Sugano T., Freymueller J., Kaufman M., Larsen C.F., Cross R., Inazu D.","Gravity measurements in southeastern Alaska reveal negative gravity rate of change caused by glacial isostatic adjustment",2010,"Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth","115","12", B12406,"","",,,10.1029/2009JB007194,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650034770&partnerID=40&md5=784b5f5ff1c6ce47eb3370426ac77258","Earthquake Research Institute, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, 113-0032, Japan; Key Laboratory of Computational Geodynamics, Graduate University of Chinese Academy of Science, 19 Yuquanlu, Shijingshanqu, Beijing 100049, China; Research Center for Prediction of Earthquakes and Volcanic Eruptions, Tohoku University, Sendai, 980-8578, Japan; Geophysical Institute, University of Alaska, 903 Koyukuk Dr., Fairbanks, AK 99775-7320, United States","Sun, W., Earthquake Research Institute, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, 113-0032, Japan, Key Laboratory of Computational Geodynamics, Graduate University of Chinese Academy of Science, 19 Yuquanlu, Shijingshanqu, Beijing 100049, China; Miura, S., Research Center for Prediction of Earthquakes and Volcanic Eruptions, Tohoku University, Sendai, 980-8578, Japan; Sato, T., Research Center for Prediction of Earthquakes and Volcanic Eruptions, Tohoku University, Sendai, 980-8578, Japan; Sugano, T., Earthquake Research Institute, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, 113-0032, Japan; Freymueller, J., Geophysical Institute, University of Alaska, 903 Koyukuk Dr., Fairbanks, AK 99775-7320, United States; Kaufman, M., Geophysical Institute, University of Alaska, 903 Koyukuk Dr., Fairbanks, AK 99775-7320, United States; Larsen, C.F., Geophysical Institute, University of Alaska, 903 Koyukuk Dr., Fairbanks, AK 99775-7320, United States; Cross, R., Geophysical Institute, University of Alaska, 903 Koyukuk Dr., Fairbanks, AK 99775-7320, United States; Inazu, D., Research Center for Prediction of Earthquakes and Volcanic Eruptions, Tohoku University, Sendai, 980-8578, Japan","For the past 300 years, southeastern Alaska has undergone rapid ice-melting and land uplift attributable to global warming. Corresponding crustal deformation (3 cm/yr) caused by the Little Ice Age retreat is detectable with modern geodetic techniques such as GPS and tidal gauge measurements. Geodetic deformation provides useful information for assessing ice-melting rates, global warming effects, and subcrustal viscosity. Nevertheless, integrated geodetic observations, including gravity measurements, are important. To detect crustal deformation caused by glacial isostatic adjustment and to elucidate the viscosity structure in southeastern Alaska, Japanese and U.S. researchers began a joint 3-year project in 2006 using GPS, Earth tide, and absolute gravity measurements. A new absolute gravity network was established, comprising five sites around Glacier Bay, near Juneau, Alaska. This paper reports the network's gravity measurements during 2006-2008. The bad ocean model in this area hindered ocean loading correction: Large tidal residuals remain in the observations. Accurate tidal correction necessitated on-site tidal observation. Results show high observation precision for all five stations: <μ Gal. The gravity rate of change was found to be -3.5 to -5.6 μGal/yr in the gravity network. Furthermore, gravity results obtained during the 3 years indicate a similar gravity change rate. These gravity data are anticipated for application in geophysical studies of southeastern Alaska. Using gravity and vertical displacement data, we constructed a quantity to remove viscoelastic effects. The observations are thus useful to constrain present-day ice thickness changes. A gravity bias of about -13.2 ± 0.1 mGal exists between the Potsdam and current FG5 gravity data. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"crustal deformation; Earth tide; geodetic network; global warming; GPS; gravimetry; gravity survey; ice retreat; ice thickness; isostasy; Little Ice Age; snowmelt; uplift; Alaska; Glacier Bay; United States",,,,,,"Arbic, B.K., Garner, S.T., Hallberg, R.W., Simmons, H.L., The accuracy of surface elevations in forward global barotropic and baroclinic tide models (2004) Deep Sea Res., 51, pp. 3069-3101; Baker, T.F., Bos, M.S., Validating Earth and ocean tide models using tidal gravity measurements (2003) Geophys. J. Int., 152 (2), pp. 468-485; Boy, J.-P., Ray, R., Hinderer, J., Diurnal atmospheric tide and induced gravity variations (2006) J. Geodyn., 41, pp. 253-258; Carrere, L., Lyard, F., Modeling the barotropic response of the global ocean to atmospheric wind and pressure forcing-comparisons with observations (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30 (6), p. 1275. , doi:10.1029/2002GL016473; Chao, B.F., Ray, R.D., Oceanic tidal angular momentum and Earth's rotation variations (1997) Prog. Oceanogr., 40, pp. 399-421; Chao, B.F., Ray, R.D., Gipson, J.M., Egbert, G.D., Ma, C., Diurnal/semidiurnal polar motion excited by oceanic tidal angular momentum (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101 (B9), pp. 20151-20163. , doi:10.1029/96JB01649; Chelton, D.B., Enfield, D.B., Ocean signals in tide gauge records (1986) J. Geophys. Res., 91 (B9), pp. 9081-9098. , doi:10.1029/JB091iB09p09081; Chree, C., The equations of an isotropic elastic solid in polar and cylindrical coordinates, their solution and application (1899) Trans. Cambridge Philos. Soc., 14, p. 250; Defant, A., (1961) Physical Oceanography, 2. , Pergamon, New York; De Viron, O., Boy, J.-P., Goosse, H., Geodetic effects of the ocean response to atmospheric forcing in an ocean general circulation model (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. B03411. , doi:10.1029/2003JB002837; Dickman, S.R., Theoretical investigation of the oceanic inverted barometer hypothesis (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93 (B12), pp. 14941-14946. , doi:10.1029/JB093iB12p14941; Dickman, S.R., The self-consistent dynamic pole tide in non global oceans (1988) Geophys. J., 94, pp. 519-543; Dickman, S.R.